      <title>Dark patches on Venus could be signs of microbial life</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANA new study theorizes that the dark patches on Venus may be a sign that there's microbial life in the planet's lower atmosphere. According to a paper published in the journal Astrobiology, climate models suggest Venus had a habitable climate and liquid water for 2 billion years, before a runaway greenhouse gas effect raised surface temperatures and turned the atmosphere toxic.The research suggests that microorganisms may be living in the planet's lower cloud layer, which has a stable temperature and more Earth-like atmospheric pressure.Dark patches on Venus could be microbial blooms made of sulfuric acid and other light-absorbing particles, which can persist for days while changing shape and contrast.Certain bacteria on Earth can survive in high altitudes after being swept into the atmosphere; others have also been known to thrive in extremely harsh environments.Thus far, the probes that have explored Venus have been incapable of distinguishing between organic and inorganic particles.So until a new contraption gets there, no one knows for sure if life does exist on the hottest planet in the solar system.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of Venus' runaway greenhouse effect2. Possible microbial life in Venus' lower to middle cloud layer3. Dark patches continuously changing shape and contrast, could be microbial blooms4. Depiction of similar bacteria on EarthVOICEOVER (in English): "Climate models suggest Venus had a habitable climate and liquid water for 2 billion years, before a runaway greenhouse gas effect raised surface temperatures and turned the atmosphere toxic.""New research now suggests that microorganisms may be living in the planet's lower cloud layer, which has a stable temperature and more Earth-like atmospheric pressure.""Dark patches on Venus could be microbial blooms made of sulfuric acid and other light-absorbing particles, which can persist for days while changing shape and contrast.""Certain bacteria on Earth can survive in high altitudes after being swept into the atmosphere; others have also been known to thrive in extremely harsh environments."SOURCES: Astrobiology,  University of Wisconsin-Madisonhttps://www.liebertpub.com/doi/full/10.1089/ast.2017.1783https://phys.org/news/2018-03-life-adrift-clouds-venus.html***]]></description>
