      <title>RNA-based plant vaccine could supplant chemical pesticides</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANConventional pesticides are a double-edged sword that scientists are now seeking to replace with more natural RNA-based plant vaccines.The U.S. Department of Agriculture estimates that without pesticides, roughly 70 percent of the world's crops would be lost to pests. But such chemicals are toxic  killing insects but also affecting the rest of the environment.New research in the Plant Biology Journal details an approach that involves directly spraying plant leaves with an RNA-based vaccine. Developed in France and Finland, this inoculates against specific pests or pathogens.The vaccine triggers a process called RNA interference, which prevents invading RNA strands from carrying out their functions, thus causing the pest to die.RNA molecules in the vaccine do not negatively affect the host plant. The RNA also has the added benefit of being biodegradable because it breaks down quickly.Instead of chemical synthesis, scientists used a bacteria-eating virus called a bacteriophage to help generate the RNA.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Conventional pesticides crucial to crops, but full of toxic chemicals2. RNA-based vaccine developed to target specific pests3. Vaccine interferes with pest's RNA processes4. Vaccine biodegradable, doesn't accumulate in the environmentVOICEOVER (in English): "Without pesticides, roughly 70 percent of the world's crops would be lost to pests. But such chemicals are toxic  killing insects but also affecting the rest of the environment.""A new approach developed in Finland and France involves directly spraying plant leaves with an RNA-based vaccine that inoculates against specific pests or pathogens.""The vaccine triggers a process called RNA interference, which prevents invading RNA strands from carrying out their functions, thus causing the pest to die.""RNA molecules in the vaccine do not negatively affect the host plant. The RNA also has the added benefit of being biodegradable because it break down quickly."SOURCES: Plant Biology Journal, University of Helsinki, United States Department of Agriculturehttps://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/pbi.12904https://www.helsinki.fi/en/news/life-science/a-vaccine-for-edible-plants-a-new-plant-protection-method-on-the-horizonhttps://nifa.usda.gov/blog/global-scientists-meet-integrated-pest-management-idea-sharing***]]></description>
