      <title>Scientists harvest vegetables from Antarctic greenhouse</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANAt a greenhouse in the least hospitable continent on Earth, scientists have successfully farmed their first batch of fresh greens.Deutsche Welle reports that German researchers at Neumayer Station III have developed a method to grow fruits and vegetables without sunlight or soil.A high-tech greenhouse in Antarctica was used to grow produce despite subzero temperatures outside. Optimized lighting, a closed water system, and controlled levels of carbon dioxide were used.The first harvest yielded 3.6 kilograms of fresh greens, 18 cucumbers, and 70 radishes.Scientists are working on several different types of plants, and hope to harvest 4 to 5 kilos of fruits and veggies a week by May of 2018.The Antarctic project, named EDEN-ISS and run by the German Aerospace Center, aims to produce a wider range of produce that could feed future human missions to the moon or Mars.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Plants grown without sunlight or oil 2. Different plants grown in high-tech greenhouse in Antarctica3. Amount of vegetables harvested in Antarctic greenhouse4. Depiction of a greenhouse on MarsVOICEOVER (in English): "Researchers finding a way to cultivate plants in space have developed a method to grow fruits and vegetables without sunlight or soil.""A high-tech greenhouse in Antarctica was used to grow produce despite subzero temperatures outside. Optimized lighting, a closed water system, and controlled levels of carbon dioxide were used.""The first harvest yielded 3.6 kilograms of fresh greens, 18 cucumbers, and 70 radishes.""The Antarctic project run by the German Aerospace Center aims to produce a wider range of produce that could feed future human missions to the moon or Mars."SOURCES: EDEN ISS, Deutsche Wellehttp://eden-iss.net/http://www.dw.com/en/scientists-harvest-antarctic-greenhouse-vegetables/a-43265721***]]></description>
