      <title>Area of Great Pacific Garbage Patch 16 times larger than previously estimated</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANA new study suggests the Great Pacific Garbage Patch could be 16 times larger than previous estimates.  The results of a three-year study beginning in 2015, commissioned by the Ocean Cleanup Foundation, were published in the journal Scientific Reports on Thursday. With 30 vessels and a C-130 Hercules aircraft, researchers catalogued a sample of over a million pieces of plastic, mostly comprised of microplastics less than 0.5 centimeters in diameter, according to CBC News. The study estimates the patch could contain more than 1.8 trillion pieces of microplastics. Scientists say there are more than 79,000 tonnes of plastic in a 1.6 million square kilometer area of the North Pacific Ocean. Researchers found plastic bottles, containers, packaging straps, lids, ropes and fishing nets among the other refuse that had been collecting for decades. As the plastics breakdown into smaller pieces, they threaten marine life that can eat them and die from them. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Great Pacific Garbage Patch2. Research vessels and a C-130 collecting samples of plastics pollution3. Estimated weight and size of garbage patch4. Researchers pulling plastics garbage out from oceanVOICEOVER (in English): "Results of a new three-year study beginning in 2015 suggests the Great Pacific Garbage Patch could be 16 times larger than previous estimates."  "With 30 vessels and a C-130 Hercules aircraft, researchers catalogued a sample of over a million pieces of plastic, mostly microplastics less than 0.5 centimeters in diameter.""Scientists say there are more than 79,000 tonnes  equal to 500 jumbo jets   of plastic in a 1.6 million square kilometer area  around three times the size of France   of the North Pacific Ocean." "Researchers found plastic bottles, containers, packaging straps, lids, ropes and fishing nets among the other refuse that had been collecting for decades."SOURCES: CBC News, Scientific Reportshttp://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/great-pacific-garbage-patch-1.4582626https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-018-22939-w***]]></description>
