      <title>NASA to launch new Mars mission in California</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANCalifornia will play host to the first interplanetary launch from the U.S. west coast next month.NASA will launch their insight mission to Mars from the Vandenberg Air Force in California on the morning of May 5, 2018. The higher it gets, the more visible it'll be to more of the state. NASA reckons 10 million Californians will be able to see it.Protected by an aeroshell, the lander will travel for around 6 months to the red planet.Once close to the atmosphere it'll begin a 6-minute descent around 80 miles from the Martian surface.As it approaches the surfaces, the spacecraft will get rid of its heat shielding and deploy a parachute. Once there, the Insight lander will remain stationary and not move around. NASA will use to probe the Martian surface and analyze soil samples from deep inside the planet.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of takeoff location and where it can be viewed2. Depiction of Insight in space3. Depiction of Insight descending to Martian surface4. Depiction of Insight on the Martian surfaceVOICEOVER (in English): "In a first for the U.S. west coast, NASA will launch their Insight mission to Mars from the Vandenberg Air Force in California on May 5." "The higher it gets, the more visible it'll be. NASA reckons 10 million Californians will be able to see it  .""Protected by an aeroshell, the lander will travel for around 6 months before reaching  Mars." "Once close to the atmosphere it'll begin a 6-minute descent around 80 miles from the surface.""As it descends, the spacecraft will get rid of its heat shielding and deploy a parachute.""Once there, the Insight lander will remain stationary.""NASA will use it to probe the Martian surface and analyze soil samples from deep inside the planet."SOURCES: NASAhttps://mars.nasa.gov/insight/https://www.nasa.gov/feature/jpl/bound-for-mars-countdown-to-first-interplanetary-launch-from-california***]]></description>
