      <title>Giant plastics collector about to set sail for Great Pacific Garbage Patch</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANThe Ocean Cleanup is building a giant plastic-scooping system in Alameda, California and plans to set sail as early as this summer to begin cleaning up the Great Pacific Garbage Patch.  The Great Pacific Garbage Patch has an estimated 1.8 trillion pieces of plastics brought there by ocean currents and is roughly three times the size of France, according to an article published in Scientific Reports. The Ocean Cleanup, started by 23-year-old Boyan Slat, has designed a massive 2,000-foot long, floating tube that will serve as a barrier to trap plastic.It's made from HDPE plastic and is flexible enough to bend with the waves, but rigid enough to form a U-shaped barrier to trap floating plastics pollution, according to Fast Company. A nylon screen is attached underneath to catch plastics, but not be a threat to marine life. Large floating anchors, hundreds of feet below the surface, help steady the device so it moves slower in the current than the plastic, making it possible to pick up the garbage in front of the device. Ocean Cleanup spokesperson Joost Dubois said that when the final systems are sent out to the Pacific ocean, there will be 60 floating scoops in total. Boats will come every six to eight weeks to collect the plastics and take them to shore to be recycled.   RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. The plastics collector being taken out to sea2. The plastics collector deployed at sea3. The anchoring system4. A boat coming to collect the plastics garbageVOICEOVER (in English): "The Ocean Cleanup is building a giant 2,000-foot-long plastic-scooping system in Alameda, California that will serve as a barrier to trap plastics floating in the Great Pacific Garbage Patch.""It's made from HDPE plastic and is flexible enough to bend with the waves, but rigid enough to form a U-shaped barrier to trap floating plastics pollution. A nylon screen underneath catches plastic without posing a threat to marine life." "Large floating anchors, hundreds of feet below the surface, help steady the device so it moves slower in the current than the plastic, making it possible to pick up the garbage in front of the device." "Boats will then come every six to eight weeks to collect the plastics and take them back to land to be recycled." SOURCES: Fast Company, ABC 7, Scientific Report, Inhabitathttps://www.fastcompany.com/40560810/the-revolutionary-giant-ocean-cleanup-machine-is-about-to-set-sailhttp://abc7news.com/society/the-ocean-cleanup-prepares-to-fight-plastic-with-plastic-in-alameda/3363441/https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-018-22939-whttps://inhabitat.com/the-ocean-cleanup-is-about-to-send-a-giant-plastic-collector-to-the-great-pacific-garbage-patch/***]]></description>
